goal:
Test your honeypots!

Have you ever tricked an attacker into attacking a honeypot? Or was the attacker tricked you into using it for malicious purposes?

The network created within this lab is designed to make attackers lose their minds, as everything on it is to confuse them.

You can find Dioanea as a low-interaction honeypot and two Cowrie honeypots as a medium/high-interaction honeypot for our purposes.

 

First try attacking honeypots using some tools and read what you discovered.

Later, you can exploit some honeypot vulnerabilities to make it interact with other hosts.

Try to do both of this!

 

When an attacker makes a connection to the cowrie_high host he is redirected to a specially configured real ssh server.

 

To start the Cowrie service at medium-interaction:

$ sudo su - cowrie

$ cowrie/bin/cowrie start
solution:
Before showing you a solution, the first thing performed is the network scan using Nmap to discover open ports.

$ nmap 193.20.1.0/24

Now we can divide a possible solution into three different scenarios based on the cunning of the attacker.

 

1. Dumb attacker and low interaction honeypot

The first thing that stands out is the 193.20.1.5 host which has all ports open, so the dumb attacker tries to interact with that host right away.

There is the ftp with 21 port opened, so he tries to login anonymously:

$ ftp 193.20.1.5



The attacker then injects his own malware using the put command:

$ put /malware.txt /malware.txt



The attacker thinks he's not being tracked for anonymous login but doesn't know he's attacked a honeypot, specifically dionaea which is low interaction but has been tracking his actions.

To read the logs you need to go to the folder in the following path: opt/dionaea/var/lib/dionaea/bistreams:

We can see that the stupid attacker is not anonymous as ftp leads him to believe, but that he has been tracked along with his malicious activity.

 

2. Average attacker and medium interaction honeypot

In this scenario, the attacker understands that the host with the most open ports is a honeypot and therefore tries to interact with another host.

Scan reported that host 193.20.1.2 has telnet and ssh ports opened so he tries a dictionary attack to discover a combination of username and password to log in with ssh.

Using hydra with two dictionaries of usernames and passwords that you can find in the image, a brute-force attack is performed in order to achieve our goal.

$ hydra -L usernames.txt -P passwords.txt 193.20.1.2 ssh -t 5

With one of the five combinations you are then logged in via ssh, then trying to steal the password file:

$ ssh root@193.20.1.2
$ cat etc/passwd

With cowrie, to read the logs you need to go to the folder in the following path: cowrie//var/log/cowrie/cowrie.json:

As we can see the IP address of the attacker is 193.20.1.4 and the attack is a brute-force one.

 

3. Smart attacker and high interaction honeypot

The attacker uses another network node that has a single active port to execute malicious code on the network through the node he is connected to.

In our example we run some simple code to scan the network via a bash script available in the image.

 

This practice could be useful to have information on the accessibility of the attacked host with other nodes of the same network but you can also execute other malicious code.

Now, since the node is an high-interaction honeypot, we can read log files using the following command in our prompt:

$ sudo docker cp Container_ID:cowrie/cowrie-git/var/log/cowrie/cowrie.json ~/Desktop/logs.txt

And then reading the provided logs we can see that someone executed a script that uses pings to scan the network.
